{"cursor":"16732","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"The 'Gibbs adsorption isotherm for multicomponent systems' is an equation used\nto relate the changes in concentration of a component in contact with a surface\nwith changes in the surface tension. For a binary system containing two\ncomponents, the Gibbs adsorption equation in terms of surface excess is:\n\n: -\\mathrm{d}\\gamma\\ = \\Gamma_1\\mathrm{d}\\mu_1\\, +\n:\\Gamma_2\\mathrm{d}\\mu_2\\,,\n\nwhere\n: \\gamma\\,\\! is the surface tension,\n: \\Gamma\\,\\! 1 is the surface excess of component 1,\n: \\mu\\,\\! 1 is the chemical potential of component 1.\n","linknr":204,"url":"Gibbs_isotherm","recorded":1362511917,"links":14,"instances":["chemistry","matter","chemistry","interfacial"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Surface chemistry"],"headings":["Adsorption","Conceptual explanation of equation","Location of surface and defining surface excess","The Gibbs adsorption isotherm equation","Ionic dissociation effects","Experimental methods","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/1/3/013f670cb1b09d10e373a1199e04b9e1.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/5/6/3561beb054a95d4ead43a8451708286c.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/f/b/4/fb437baccd7b252cd3006fdd8e110547.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/7/4/b/74b8eddf4b37de80c7c8eed1b64e46fc.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b8/Gibbs_image_2.png/400px-Gibbs_image_2.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/63/Gibbs_image_3.png/400px-Gibbs_image_3.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/2/b/6/2b62894498d6573fa07efb194c7ffcd2.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/2/6/52604ffc3979ce1a487573d5da2ea711.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/f/d/2/fd2c9f83ecac79926c701f3f005a1de5.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/5/d/35da860a19016d316755b6391b13da76.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c